			<p><strong>Central heat pump<a name="chp" id="chp"></a>:</strong> A type of heat pump that heats or cools an entire house or a large part of a house. They provide warm or cool air to individual rooms using ducts. Also known as a “ducted heat pump.”</p>
          <p><strong>Central warm-air furnace<a name="cwaf" id="cwaf"></a>: </strong>A type of space-heating equipment where a central combustor or  resistance unit (generally using natural gas, fuel oil, propane, or  electricity) provides warm air through ducts leading to various rooms.  Consumption and expenditure estimates for furnaces exclude furnace fans and  blowers. Heat pumps are not included in this category. </p>
          <p><strong>Climate region: <a name="clim_zone" id="clim_zone"></a></strong> A set of climatically distinct areas, defined by long-term weather  conditions that affect the heating and cooling loads in buildings. In 2009,  RECS began using&nbsp;<a href="https://energy.gov/eere/buildings/building-america-climate-specific-guidance"><em>Building America Climate Regions</em></a><em>,</em>&nbsp;which  are defined using <a href="#hdd">heating degree days</a>,  average temperatures, and precipitation data. Before 2009, RECS used&nbsp;<a href="/consumption/residential/maps.php">seven distinct climate categories</a>&nbsp;originally  identified by the American Institute of Architects (AIA) for the U.S.  Department of Energy and the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development. </p>
          <p><strong>Clothes dryer: </strong>An appliance in the home that dries laundry, such as clothing and sheets  using heat and rapid air movement. The hot air used can be heated by  electricity, natural gas, or propane.</p>
          <p><strong>Clothes washer:</strong> An appliance in the home used to wash laundry. Clothes washers can open  from the top or front. The machine is powered by an electric motor.</p>
		  <p><strong>Community solar generation:</strong> Electricity generated offsite from a housing unit using photovoltaic  (PV) panels. RECS does not capture housing units that use community solar  generation as part of solar estimates.</p>
          <p><strong>Compact </strong><strong>fluorescent (CFL) bulb<a name="cfbl" id="cfbl"></a>:</strong> Lightbulbs that use fluorescent lighting technology, but in a format  that can be used in common household lighting fixtures. CFLs are one of three  types of lighting included in the 2020 RECS questionnaire. (See <a href="#Incandescent_Bulb">Incandescent bulb</a> and <a href="#ledbulb">LED bulb</a>)</p>
		  <p><strong>Concrete slab:</strong> The foundation of a home or building that is solid, poured concrete. </p>
          <p><strong>Conditional  end-use intensity<a name="end_inten" id="end_inten"></a> (CEUI): </strong>A measure of energy efficiency that allows comparisons across housing  units by adjusting either the end-use consumption or expenditures for the  effects of certain characteristics, such as square footage or number of  household members. </p>
		  <p><strong>Condominium or cooperative:</strong> (See&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#apart">Apartment</a>)</p>
          <p><strong>Condominium or cooperative  fee:</strong> When living in condominiums or cooperatives, residents pay this fee to  the homeowners&rsquo; association for maintenance, management, insurance, and in some  cases, utilities.</p>
          <p><strong>Consumption:<a name="consumption" id="consumption"></a></strong> The amount of electricity or natural gas delivered by an energy supplier  to a housing unit during the reference year, electricity generated via on-site  renewables (e.g., solar panels) and consumed at the housing unit, or the amount  of fuel oil or kerosene and propane purchased. Total site consumption in RECS  tables and analyses includes electricity, natural gas, fuel oil or kerosene,  and propane. Wood consumption estimates are also produced but not included in  total site energy consumption.</p>
          <p><a name="cstove" id="cstove"></a><strong>Cooled square footage:</strong> The floor area in a housing unit that is cooled by air-conditioning  equipment. </p>
          <p><strong>Cooling Degree Days<a name="cdd" id="cdd"></a> (CDD):</strong> A measure of how hot a location was over a period of time  relative to a base temperature. In the RECS tables and analyses, the base  temperature is 65°  Fahrenheit, and the period of time is one year. The CDDs for a single day is  the difference between that day's average outside temperature and the base  temperature if the daily average is greater than the base; CDD is zero if the  daily average outside temperature is less than or equal to the base  temperature. The number of CDDs for a longer period of time is the sum of the  daily CDDs for the days in that period. Average daily temperature is the mean  of the maximum and minimum temperature for a 24-hour period. Local weather  station CDD data (annual and 30-year averages) from the National Climate Data  Center are linked to each RECS household case. </p>
<p><strong>Cord of wood:</strong> (See&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#woodcon">Wood consumption</a>)</p>
          <p><strong>Crawl space:</strong> Space where a person cannot walk upright between the ground and the  first floor of a house. </p>
          <p><strong>Cubic foot  (cf):</strong> Standard unit of volume used as a <a href="#natural_gas1">natural gas</a> measure. The volume of gas  contained in a 1x1x1 foot cube at standard temperature and pressure (60° Fahrenheit and 14.73 pounds standard  per square inch).  </p>
<p><strong>Current  dollars:</strong> Unless  otherwise noted, all dollar values in the RECS tables and analyses are  expressed in the current U.S. dollars at the time of data collection. The  dollar amounts have not been adjusted for inflation. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="d" id="d"></a>D</div><br />
          <p><strong>Dehumidifier: </strong>A device that removes moisture from the air,  and are typically used in the summer in warm climates or year round in humid  climates. Can also be used in basements or other areas that are too damp. Can  be either small, portable units or whole-home units. </p>
		  <p><strong>Dishwasher: </strong>An appliance used for automatically cleaning dishware, utensils, and  cutlery. As of 1988, dishwashers must be equipped with an option to dry without  heat. </p>
          <p><a name="dis_gen" id="#dis-gen"></a><strong>Distributed solar generation</strong>:<a name="dis_gen1"></a> Electricity generated at a housing unit through photovoltaic (PV)  panels. (See&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#s_energy1">Solar Energy</a>)</p>
		  <p><strong>Ductless  heat pump (mini-split): </strong>A type of heat pump that heats or cools smaller spaces, either a single  room or part of a house. They do not require any ductwork, which is why they  are popular for additions or in older homes. Consists of an outdoor unit and an  indoor unit, otherwise known as a &ldquo;head&rdquo;. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="e" id="e"></a>E</div><br />
		  <p><strong>Electric vehicle (EV):</strong><a name="ethn" id="ethn"></a></strong> A general term for  any on-road licensed vehicle that can plug into an electric power source and  uses electric power to move. EVs plug into a source of electricity and store  power in a battery pack for all or part of their power needs. Includes Battery  Electric Vehicles (BEVs) and Plug-in Hybrid Vehicles (PHEVs). Can also be  referred to as Plug-in Electric Vehicles (PEV).</p>
          <p><strong>End use<a name="end_use" id="end_use"></a>:</strong> A specific energy-consuming function for which  fuels (energy sources) are ultimately used in the household. The amount of  energy used for end uses is modeled using survey variables, weather data, and  engineering estimates of consumption rather than being directly measured. RECS  has 28 energy consumption and expenditure end-use categories. </p>
          <p><strong>Energy supplier: </strong> A company that provides  energy to customers. An energy supplier can be a utility company that provides  electricity or natural gas through powerlines or pipelines, or a bulk fuel  supplier that delivers fuel oil, kerosene, or propane to a tank at the home.  The RECS Energy Supplier Survey (ESS) collects information from energy  suppliers who provide electricity, natural gas, fuel oil, kerosene, or propane  to households. The ESS does not collect information about wood usage or  cash-and-carry bulk fuel purchases. </p>
          <p><strong>Ethnicity:</strong><a name="ethn1" id="ethn1"></a></strong> The householder's self-identification as being Hispanic or Latino. RECS  questions adhere to&nbsp;<a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-1997-10-30/pdf/97-28653.pdf">standards issued  by the Office of Management and Budget</a>, which specify that  race and ethnicity are two separate and distinct concepts. </p>
          <p><strong>Evaporative  cooler (swamp cooler): </strong>A type of cooling equipment that uses the evaporation of water to cool  air. This type of equipment is commonly found in warm, dry climates. </p>
          <p><strong>Expenditures: </strong>Money charged for the energy delivered to a housing unit during a given  period of time. For the RECS tables and analyses, all expenditure statistics  are presented on an annualized basis. The total dollar amount includes base  service charges and fees, and state and local taxes. It excludes late fees,  one-time service fees, merchandise, and equipment repair charges. Electricity  and natural gas expenditures are for the amount of those energy sources  consumed. Fuel oil, kerosene, and propane expenditures are for the amount of  fuel purchased, which may differ from the amount of fuel consumed. For  households that do not pay their fuel supplier directly, the expenditures for  fuels are imputed. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="f" id="f"></a>F</div><br />
          <p><strong>Fireplace:</strong> A structure made of brick, stone, or metal that is built into the wall  and designed to contain a fire. A <a href="#wood1">wood or pellet stove</a> is  a freestanding fireplace that can be detached from its chimney. Fireplaces can  burn wood, natural gas, or propane, or can use electricity.</p>
          <p><a name="floorspace" id="floorspace"></a><strong>Freezer (stand-alone): </strong>An electric motor-driven refrigeration unit designed for storing food at  temperatures of about 0° Fahrenheit.  A freezer is a stand-alone appliance, not part of a refrigerator, that can be  an upright model (vertical unit with the door opening outward) or a chest model  (horizontal unit with the door opening upward).</p>
          <p><strong>Frost-free freezer:</strong> A freezer, either separated from or attached to a refrigerator that  automatically defrosts, usually on 12- or 24- hour cycles.</p>
          <p><strong>Fuel:</strong> The energy sources used by a household on site. The energy  sources identified as a characteristic for the RECS tables and microdata files  are electricity, <a href="#natural_gas1">natural gas</a>, fuel oil or <a href="#kerosene">kerosene</a>, <a href="#propane">propane</a>, <a href="#wood">wood</a>, and <a href="#Stwh">solar thermal</a>. Fuel consumption and  expenditures estimates are produced for electricity, natural gas, fuel oil or kerosene,  and propane only. Wood consumption estimates are also produced but not included  in total site consumption. </p>
		  <p><strong>Fuel oil<a name="fuel_oil" id="fuel_oil"></a>: </strong>A subset of distillate fuel oil, which is a general classification of  liquid petroleum products. Residential fuel oils are less volatile than  gasoline and are burned for space heating or water heating. No. 2 fuel oil is  the most common type used in homes. Because <a href="#kerosene">kerosene</a>  use is relatively rare, fuel oil and kerosene were combined into a single fuel  category beginning with the 2015 RECS. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="g" id="g"></a>G</div><br />
          <p><strong>Geothermal  or ground source heat pump: </strong>A type of heat pump that uses the natural heat  storage ability of the earth or the groundwater to heat or cool a home. The  earth can absorb and store heat energy from the sun. To use that stored energy,  heat is extracted from the earth through a liquid medium (groundwater or an  anti-freeze solution) and is pumped to the heat pump or heat exchanger. There,  the heat is used to heat the home. In the summer, the process is reversed and  indoor heat is extracted from the home and transferred to the earth through the  liquid. It is also referred to as a closed-loop system or a geothermal heat  pump.</p>
          <div class="glossary_title"><a name="h" id="h"></a>H</div><br />
          <p><strong>HDD: </strong> See <a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#hdd">Heating Degree  Days</a></p>
          <p><strong>Heat pump:<a name="heat_pump" id="heat_pump"></a> </strong> A type of heating and  air-conditioning equipment that draws heat into a building from outside and,  during the cooling season, ejects heat from the building to the outside. Heat  pumps are vapor-compression refrigeration systems whose indoor/outdoor coils  are used reversibly as condensers or evaporators, depending on the need for  heating or cooling.</p>
          <p><strong>Heated square  footage:<a name="heat_foot"></a></strong> The floor area in a housing unit that is heated by any heating equipment. </p>
          <p><strong>Heating Degree Days<a name="hdd" id="hdd"></a> (HDD):</strong> A measure of how cold a location was over a period of time, relative to  a base temperature. In the RECS tables and analyses, the base temperature used  is 65°  Fahrenheit and the period of time is one year. The heating degree-days for a  single day is the difference between the base temperature and the day's average  outside temperature if the daily average is less than the base, and zero if the  daily average outside temperature is greater than or equal to the base temperature.  The heating degree-days for a longer period of time are the sum of the daily  heating degree-days for days in that period. Average daily temperature is the  mean of the maximum and minimum temperature for a 24-hour period. Local weather  station heating degree day data (annual and 30-year averages) from the National  Climate Data Center are linked to each RECS household case. </p>
          <p><a name="heat_equip1" id="heat_equip1"></a><strong>Heating  equipment:<a name="heat_equip" id="heat_equip"></a> </strong>The equipment used for heating ambient air in a housing unit,  such as a central warm-air furnace; heat pump; built-in electric units; steam  or hot-water system; stove; room heater; fireplace; or portable heater.  (See&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#cwaf">Central warm-air  furnace</a>;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#heat_pump">Heat pump</a>;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#bie_unit">Built-in  electric units</a>;&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#shw_system">Steam or  hot-water system</a>;&nbsp;<a href="#wood1">Wood or pellet stove</a>,&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#oil_gas">Built-in oil or  gas room heater</a>)</p> 
          <p><strong>Household<a name="hh" id="hh"></a>:</strong> A household consists of all people who occupy a particular  housing unit as their usual residence or who live there at the time of the  interview and have no usual residence elsewhere. Occupants can be related or  unrelated. In the RECS tables and analyses, the number of households is the  same as the number of occupied housing units. </p>
<p><strong>Household  income: </strong> Respondent-reported total combined annual income from all sources  (before taxes and deductions) from all household members. </p>
          <p><strong>Household  member</strong>: (See <a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#hh">Household</a>)</p>
 
 <p><a name="House_Unit1" id="House_Unit1"></a><strong>Housing unit: <a name="House_Unit" id="House_Unit"></a></strong> A house, apartment, group of rooms, or single room if it is  either occupied or intended for occupancy as separate living quarters by a  family, an individual, or a group of unrelated persons. Separate living  quarters means the occupants live and eat separately from other persons in the  house or apartment and have direct access from the outside of the building or  through a common hall—that is, they can get to their unit without going through  someone else's living quarters. Housing units do not include group quarters  such as dormitories or military barracks.</p>
         <p><strong>Humidifier:</strong> A device that adds moisture to the air and is typically used in the winter in cold climates, or year round in dry climates. Can be either small, portable units or whole-home units. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="i" id="i"></a>I</div><br />
          <strong>Incandescent bulb<a name="Incandescent_Bulb" id="Incandescent_Bulb"></a>:</strong> A type of lightbulb that produces visible light by heating a tiny coil or filament of tungsten wire via electric current to such a high temperature that it glows. RECS estimates of incandescent bulbs also include halogen bulbs. Incandescent bulbs are one of three types of lighting included in the 2020 RECS questionnaire. (See <a href="#cfbl">Compact fluorescent bulb</a> and <a href="#ledbulb">LED bulb</a>)</p>
 <p><strong>Induction cooktop<a name="inten" id="inten"></a>:</strong> A type of cooktop that uses electromagnetic technology to generate heat directly in magnetic cookware instead of on the cooktop. </p>
          <p><strong>Intensities<a name="inten" id="inten"></a>:</strong> The ratio of energy consumption or expenditures to another metric. In RECS, intensities are provided per housing unit, per household member, and per square foot.
</p>
       <div class="glossary_title"><a name="j" id="j"></a>J</div>
       <p>&nbsp;</p>
          <div class="glossary_title"><a name="k" id="k"></a>K</div><br />
          <p><a name="kerosene1" id="kerosene1"></a><strong>Kerosene<a name="kerosene" id="kerosene"></a>:</strong> A distilled product of oil or coal with the generic name kerosene, having properties similar to those of No. 1 fuel oil. Beginning with the 2015 RECS, kerosene is included with data and estimates for <a href="#fuel-oil">fuel oil</a>.</p>
          <p><strong>Kilowatthour (kWh)<a name="kilowatthours" id="kilowatthours"></a>:</strong> A measure of electricity defined as a derived unit of work or energy,  measured as 1 kilowatt (1,000 watts) of power expended for 1 hour. One kWh is  equivalent to 3,412 British thermal units. (See&nbsp;<a href="#British_thermal_units">British thermal units (Btu)</a>)</p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="l" id="l"></a>L</div><br />
<p><strong>Light-emitting </strong><strong> diode (LED) bulb<a name="ledbulb" id="ledbulb"></a>:</strong> A type of highly efficient directional lighting consisting of a two-lead semiconductor that emits light when activated. LEDs are one of three types of lighting included in the 2020 RECS questionnaire. (See <a href="#cfbl">Compact fluorescent bulb</a> and <a href="#Incandescent_Bulb">Incandescent bulb</a>) </p>
          <p><a name="lpg" id="lpg"></a><strong>Liquefied petroleum gas (LPG):</strong> (See&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#propane">Propane</a>)</p>
          <p><strong>Low-Income Home Energy Assistance  Program (LIHEAP<a name="liheap" id="liheap"></a></strong><strong>):<a name="liheap" id="liheap2"></a></strong>&nbsp;A program that provides assistance to eligible low-income  households in paying the costs of heating or cooling their housing units.  States administer the program using funds from the federal government.</p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="m" id="m"></a>M</div><br />
          <p><strong>Master metering: </strong>Measurement  of electricity or natural gas consumed by several housing units in a building  (or group of buildings) by using a single meter. Master metering is more common  in older, multifamily apartment buildings. RECS identifies households that pay  fuel costs through rent or condo fees, but it does not specifically identify a  housing unit that is part of a master-metered building.</p>
<p><strong>Metric  conversion factors:<a name="Metric_Fact" id="Metric_Fact"></a> </strong>Estimates are presented in U.S. customary measures. Square footage  estimates may be converted to metric units by using this relationship: 1 square  foot is approximately equal to 0.0929 square meters. Energy estimates may be  converted to metric units by using the relationship: 1 British thermal unit is  approximately equal to 1,055 joules, and one kilowatthour equals 3,600,000  joules. One gigajoule is approximately 278 kWh.</p>
          <p><strong>Metropolitan or  Micropolitan Statistical Area<a name="metro" id="metro"></a>:</strong> A Metropolitan Statistical Area is a county or group of contiguous  counties that contain at least one city of 50,000 inhabitants or more, or an  urbanized area of at least 50,000 inhabitants and a total population of the  metropolitan statistical area is at least 100,000 (in New England, 75,000). A  Micropolitan Statistical Area, contains a principal city with at least 10,000  inhabitants, but not more than 50,000 inhabitants. The contiguous counties are  included in a Metropolitan or Micropolitan Statistical Area if, according to  certain criteria, they are essentially metropolitan in character and are  socially and economically integrated with the central city. Both Metropolitan  and Micropolitan Statistical Areas are defined by the U.S. Office of Management  and Budget. </p>
          <p><strong>Microwave oven: </strong>A household cooking appliance with a compartment designed to cook or  heat food by means of microwave radiation. </p>
          <p><a name="mobileh" id="mobileh"></a><strong>Mobile home:</strong> A housing unit built off-site on a movable chassis and moved to a home site. A mobile home may be placed on a permanent or temporary foundation and may contain one or more rooms. A prefabricated or modular home assembled on-site is a single-family housing unit and not a mobile home.<a name="multifi" id="multifi"></a></p>
          
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="n" id="n"></a>N</div><br />
          <p><strong><a name="natural_gas1" id="natural_gas1"></a>Natural gas:<a name="natural_gas" id="natural_gas"></a> </strong> A naturally occurring hydrocarbon gas (mostly methane) delivered  as an energy source to individual buildings by underground pipelines from a  central utility company. Natural gas does not refer to <a href="#propane">propane</a>. </p>

<div class="glossary_title"><a name="o" id="o"></a>O</div><br />
          <p><strong> Occupied  housing unit:</strong> A unit with someone living in it as a usual or permanent place of residence. </p>
          <p><a name="oven"></a><strong>Oven:</strong> An appliance with a thermally insulated compartment that supplies heat and is used for cooking food. <a href="#t-oven">Toaster ovens</a> are not considered ovens. Ovens with a combined stove top or burners together in one unit are considered <a href="#range-cook">ranges</a>. </p>
          <p><strong>Owned or rented<a name="owned_rented" id="owned_rented"></a>:</strong> A housing unit is classified as&nbsp;<em>Owned</em>&nbsp;when  it is occupied by someone in the household who is named on the deed, mortgage,  or contract to purchase the unit. All other housing units are classified  as&nbsp;<em>Rented</em>. The rent may be paid by an occupant, by someone  not living in the unit, or the unit may be occupied rent free. <em>Rent free</em> means the unit is not owned by  the occupant and no money is paid or contracted for rent. Such units are  usually provided in exchange for services rendered or as an allowance or favor  from a relative or friend not living in the unit. Unless shown separately,  rent-free households are grouped with rented households. </p>
          <div class="glossary_title"><a name="p" id="p"></a>P</div><br />
          <p><strong>Payment method  for energy bills:</strong> Method by which fuel suppliers or utility companies were paid for all  electricity, natural gas, fuel oil, kerosene, or propane used by a household.  Households responsible for paying energy suppliers directly are shown in RECS  tables as&nbsp;<em>All paid by household.</em>&nbsp;Households  who paid some fuel or end-use charges through rent or a condo fee are shown  as&nbsp;<em>Some paid, some included in rent or condo fee</em>.  Households for which all fuels and end uses were included in the rent or condo  fee were classified as&nbsp;<em>All included in rent or condo  fee</em>. If a household did not fall into any of those three categories,  it was classified as&nbsp;<em>Other</em>. This category  includes households for which fuel bills were paid by a third party such as a  housing authority or a relative.</p>
          <p><strong>Portable </strong><strong>electric  heater:</strong> A heater that uses electricity and can be picked up and moved.</p>
          <p><strong>Portable kerosene heater:</strong> A heater that uses kerosene and can be picked up and moved.</p>
          <p><strong>Primary  electricity<a name="prim_ele" id="prim_ele"></a>:</strong> The amount of electricity delivered to housing units as well as the  energy used to produce and deliver the electricity. Primary electricity is site  (delivered) electricity plus conversion losses in the generation process at the  utility plant and energy losses incurred in transmission and distribution.&nbsp;  In all RECS tables and analyses, electricity is represented as site energy.</p>
        <p><a name="prim_res1" id="prim_res1"></a><strong>Primary  residence<a name="prim_res" id="prim_res"></a>:</strong> A <a href="#House_Unit1">housing unit</a> in  which a householder spends the largest part of the year and is the  householder's usual or permanent place of residence. A primary residence is  typically a year-round housing unit. If a seasonal unit happened to be occupied  for at least half of the year by the householder, the unit would be considered  a primary residence.</p>
<p><strong>Programmable  thermostat: </strong>A thermostat that can be programmed to adjust the temperature settings  for heating or cooling at predetermined times.</p>
          <p><a name="propane"></a><strong>Propane:</strong> The most common type of liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) supplied to RECS  households. Propane is usually delivered by tank trucks and stored near the  residence in a tank or cylinder until used, but it can also be purchased in  canisters from retail stores. In RECS tables and analyses, propane also  includes similar fuel gases, such as butane, supplied to a residence in liquid  form. The 2015 and 2020 RECS do not include propane purchased in canisters from  retail stores in estimates of propane use. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="q" id="q"></a>Q</div><br />
          <p><strong>Quadrillion  (Quad):</strong> The quantity  1,000,000,000,000,000 = 10<sup>15</sup> (10 to the 15th power). In the RECS  tables, total site consumption is expressed in quadrillion Btu.</p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="r" id="r"></a>R</div><br />
          <p><strong>Race: </strong>The householder&rsquo;s self-reported racial background. The RECS race  categories are: <em>White</em>, <em>Black or African-American</em>, <em>American Indian or Alaskan Native</em>, <em>Asian</em>, and <em>Native Hawaiian or Other Pacific Islander</em>. Respondents may choose  more than one race. RECS questions adhere to &nbsp;<a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/FR-1997-10-30/pdf/97-28653.pdf">standards issued by the Office of Management and Budget</a>, which specify that  race and <a href="#ethn1">ethnicity</a>  are two separate and distinct concepts. </p>
<p><strong>Radiator:</strong> A heating unit that is usually visible within the room or space to be heated and that transfers thermal energy via steam or hot water by conduction to the surrounding air. </p>
<p><strong>Range (cooking)<a name="range-cook" id="range-cook">:</a></strong> A cooking appliance that contains both a cooktop and an oven in one  unit. Also known as a stove. </p>
          <p><a name="refri_unit" id="refri_unit"></a><strong>Refrigerator:</strong><a name="frig" id="frig"></a> A household appliance that consists of a thermally-insulated compartment  designed for storing food at a constant temperature a few degrees above the  freezing point (32° Fahrenheit). Most  refrigerators have a second compartment for freezing and storing frozen foods  at temperatures of 8° Fahrenheit or below.  </p>
          <p><a name="owned_rented1"></a><strong>Rented:</strong> (See&nbsp;<a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/residential/terminology.php#owned_rented">Owned or Rented</a>)</p>
          <p><strong>Residential  Energy Consumption Survey (RECS):</strong>&nbsp;A national sample survey conducted by the Office of Energy Demand  and Integrated Statistics of the U.S. Energy Information Administration, U.S.  Department of Energy. RECS provides baseline information on how U.S. households  use energy within the home.</p>
          <p>
          <a name="room_air" id="room_air"></a><strong>Room</strong>: A  distinguishable space within a housing unit, including living rooms, dining  rooms, <a href="#bedroom">bedrooms</a>, kitchens, lodgers' rooms,  finished basements or attic rooms, recreation rooms, permanently enclosed  porches that are suitable for year-round use, and other finished rooms. For  RECS purposes, <a href="#bathroom">bathrooms</a> are classified separately. Hallways,  pantries, unfinished attics or basements, open porches, and unfinished space  used for storage are not considered rooms for RECS purposes. </p>
          <p><a name="rse_error1" id="rse_error1"></a><strong>Relative  Standard Error<a name="rse_error" id="rse_error"></a> (RSE): </strong>A statistical measure of the extent to which a sample survey is  likely to deviate from its true value in the population. An RSE provides an  estimate of the sampling variability of a survey statistic relative to the  survey statistic itself. RSEs are expressed on a percentage scale and included  on a separate tab of each RECS data table. You can find guidance on  interpreting an RSE or creating a confidence interval for an estimate at&nbsp;<em><a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/commercial/data/what-is-an-rse.php">this EIA website</a></em><em>.</em></p>
          <p><a name="rse_factor1"></a><strong>Relative Standard Error (RSE) Column Factor</strong>&nbsp;<strong>(Shown on RECS tables from 2001 and earlier</strong><strong>)</strong><strong>:</strong> An adjustment factor that appears above each column of the detailed  tables and is used to compute RSEs. The column factor is equal to the geometric  mean of the RSEs in a particular column of the main tables.</p>
          <p><a name="rse_factor1"></a><strong>Relative Standard Error (RSE) Row Factor</strong>&nbsp;<strong>(Shown on RECS tables from 2001 and earlier)</strong><strong>:</strong> An adjustment factor that appears to the right of each row of the  detailed tables and is used to compute RSE's. The row factor is equal to the  geometric mean of the RSE&rsquo;s in a particular row of the main tables.  </p>
          <p><strong>Rural<a name="rural" id="rural"></a>:</strong> For the 2020 RECS, housing units were classified using criteria defined  by the U.S. Census Bureau based on 2010 Census data. Rural areas are considered  to be any area not in an <a href="#urban">urbanized area or urban cluster</a>.  Urbanized areas are densely settled groupings of blocks or tracts with 50,000  or more people, and urban clusters have at least 2,500 people but less than  50,000 people. Before the 2009 RECS, urban and rural classifications, as well  as city and town designations, were self-reported by respondents. </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="s" id="s"></a>S</div><br />
          <p><strong>Secondary  heating:</strong> Space-heating equipment and fuel used less often than the main  space-heating equipment. For the 2020 RECS, respondents could select only one  type of secondary heating equipment. Respondents self-report their primary and  secondary heating equipment, so it is possible that a respondent may report a  larger or more intensive equipment, such as a natural gas furnace, as their  secondary equipment, and an electric space heating as their primary space  heating equipment.</p>
          <p><strong>Separate cooktop<a name="sep_cook"></a>:</strong> Burners that are used to cook food, but are not attached to an oven.  Separate cooktops may use electricity, <a href="#natural_gas1">natural gas</a>,  or <a href="#propane">propane</a>.&nbsp; </p>
          <p><strong>Shakes:<a name="sep_cook"></a></strong> Flat pieces of  weatherproof material laid with others in a series of overlapping rows as a  covering for roofs. Shakes are similar to wood shingles, but, instead of having  a cut and smoothly planed surface, shakes have textured grooves and a rough or  rustic appearance.&nbsp; </p>
          <p><strong>Shingles  (composition or asphalt):<a name="sep_cook"></a></strong>  Flat pieces of weatherproof material laid with others in a series of overlapping rows as covering for roofs and sometimes the walls of homes. Shingles are manufactured in a variety of materials, including fiberglass, plastic, baked clay, tile, asbestos, asphalt, aluminum, and wood.</p>
          <p><strong>Siding<a name="sep_cook"></a>:</strong> An  exterior wall covering material made of wood, plastic (including vinyl), metal  (including aluminum or steel), or fiber cement. The structural walls may be  masonry or wood. Siding is generally produced in the shape of boards and  applied to the outside of a home in overlapping rows.</p>
          <p><a name="sfamily" id="sfamily"></a><strong>Single-family housing unit:</strong>  A <a href="#House_Unit1">housing unit</a> that typically provides living  space for one household or family. Single-family housing units may be detached  or attached. Attached single-family housing units are connected side-by-side by  a wall that extends ground to roof (that is, a townhouse, row house, or  duplex.) A <a href="#mobileh">mobile home</a> is not classified as a  single-family housing unit in the RECS.</p>
          <p><a name="electricity1" id="electricity1"></a><strong>Site electricity<a name="electricity" id="electricity"></a>:</strong> The amount of electricity, in <a href="#British_thermal_units">British thermal units</a> or <a href="#kilowatthours">kilowatthours</a>,  delivered to the housing unit. Site electricity does not include energy losses  in generation and transmission. Site electricity is also known as delivered  electricity. </p>
<p><a name="site_energy" id="site_energy"></a><strong>Smart meter: </strong>An electricity meter that allows two-way communication between the  customer and energy supplier. A common feature of smart meters is the  collection and storage of electricity usage at shorter time intervals (for  example, hourly or daily). </p>
<p><a name="site_energy" id="site_energy"></a><strong>Smart speaker: </strong>An internet-connected speaker that is used to control other devices within the home, such as lighting, televisions, thermostats, security systems, cameras, or locks.  </p>
<p><strong>Smart thermostat: </strong>An<strong>&nbsp;</strong>Internet-connected thermostat that can be programmed to  adjust the temperature settings for heating or cooling at predetermined times.  A smart thermostat may allow heating and cooling to be controlled remotely (for  example, through a smartphone). Smart thermostats can also learn a household&rsquo;s routine  behaviors and adjust its heating and cooling schedule to maximize efficiency. </p>
 <p><a name="s_energy1"></a><strong>Solar energy<a name="s_energy" id="s_energy"></a>:</strong> The radiant light and heat from the sun, which can be converted into electricity  using photovoltaic (PV) cells. For RECS,&nbsp;<em>Solar</em>&nbsp;is  classified as a fuel for solar thermal water heating or pool heating only.  Distributed generation via solar photovoltaic cells is classified as  electricity and not as a separate fuel or energy source. </p>
          <p><strong>Solar thermal water heating<a name="Stwh" id="Stwh"></a>:</strong> A system that heats water using special photovoltaic (PV) cells integrated with water storage to directly heat water to provide hot water to households. The hot water may then be used for space heating with a steam or hot water system, domestic hot water heating, or pool heating. </p>
          <p><strong>Space heating<a name="space_heat" id="space_heat"></a>:</strong> As an  energy <a href="#end_use">end use</a>, the use of mechanical equipment (including wood or pellet  stoves and fireplaces) to heat all, or part, of a housing unit to at least  50°F. Heat may be provided by  main or secondary space-heating equipment. Space heating is one of the major  categories of energy end-use estimates in the RECS tables and analyses. Space-heating  end use estimates do not include the energy used by furnace fans or blowers,  nor does it include the use of energy to operate appliances, such as lights,  televisions, and refrigerators, that give off heat as a byproduct. </p>
<p><strong>Square footage: </strong>The floor area of the housing unit that is enclosed by the exterior  walls. In the RECS tables and analyses, square footage includes the following: finished  and unfinished basements, finished and/or heated space in attics; and attached  garages that are heated or cooled. Square footage estimates do not include:  crawl spaces, even if they are enclosed from the weather; unfinished or  unheated attics; and sheds and other buildings that are not attached to the  house. Square footage can also be referred to as floorspace. </p>
<p><a name="shw_system1" id="shw_system1"></a><strong>Steam or  hot-water system<a name="shw_system1" id="shw_system1"></a>: </strong>A central space-heating system that supplies steam or hot water  to radiators, convectors, or pipes. There are two types of steam or hot water  systems, one more common than the other. The more common type supplies either  steam or hot water from a boiler to conventional radiators, baseboard units,  convectors, heating pipes embedded in the walls or ceilings, or heating coils  or equipment that are part of a combined heating/ventilating or  heating/air-conditioning system. The other, rarer type supplies radiant heat  through pipes that carry hot water and are held in a floor.</p>
<p><strong>Stucco<a name="stove" id="stove"></a>:</strong> A type of exterior plaster  applied as a two-or-three part coating directly onto masonry, or applied over  wood or metal lath to a log or wood frame structure.&nbsp;</p>
          <p><strong>Swimming pool  heater:</strong> Optional heating equipment integrated into a pool&rsquo;s pump system that heats  water to maintain pool water temperature at a specified level.</p>
  <p><strong>Swimming pool pump:</strong> An electric pump for filtering and circulating pool water. Includes  single-speed, two-speed, and variable-speed pool pumps.</p>
          <div class="glossary_title"><a name="t" id="t"></a>T</div><br />
          <p><strong>Temperature: </strong>Respondents&rsquo; reported estimates of the indoor temperature, which is  typically the thermostat setting. </p>
          <p><strong>Thermostat:</strong> A device that senses the temperature inside all or part of a housing  unit and adjusts the amount of heating and air conditioning produced and/or  distributed into the housing unit.</p>
          <p><strong>Toaster oven:<a name="t-oven" id="t-oven"></a></strong> Portable table-top or counter-top appliance used for heating or broiling  food. Toaster ovens are not counted as <a href="#oven">ovens</a> in  the RECS.    </p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="u" id="u"></a>U</div><br />
          <p><strong>Urban<a name="urban" id="urban"></a>:</strong> For the 2020 RECS, housing units were classified using criteria  defined by the U.S. Census Bureau based on 2010 Census data. Urbanized areas  are densely settled groupings of blocks or tracts with 50,000 or more people, and  urban clusters have at least 2,500 people, but less than 50,000 people. All  other areas are <a href="#rural">rural</a>. Before the 2009 RECS, urban  and rural classifications, as well as city and town designations, were self-reported  by respondents. <strong> </strong></p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="v" id="v"></a>V</div><br />
          <p><strong>Vacant housing  unit: </strong>A  housing unit not occupied at the time of interview. An occupied seasonal or  migratory housing unit is classified as vacant if all of its occupants have a  usual place of residence elsewhere.</p>
<div class="glossary_title"><a name="w" id="w"></a>W</div><br />
          <p><strong>Water heater:</strong> An automatically controlled, thermally insulated vessel that heats and  stores water, or a tankless device that heats and transfers hot water on  demand. In some systems, a steam or hot water system provides hot water and  heat to the home. In these systems, the water is heated by a coil that is part  of the heating system and there is not a separate hot water tank.</p>
          <p><strong>Water heater  size:</strong> Respondents  were asked the size of their water heater tank. Four categories were provided:  small (30 gallons or less), medium (31 to 49 gallons), large (50 gallons or  more), and tankless (or on-demand). </p>
<p><strong>Water heating:</strong><a name="wh" id="wh"></a> The use of energy to heat water for domestic hot water. This  category does not include energy used to heat water via a range or separate cooktop  for cooking or hot drinks, or for swimming pools. Water heating is one of the  major end-use categories in the RECS tables and analyses.</p>

          <p><strong>Whole-house fan:</strong> A  type of fan installed in the ceiling of the living space that is used for  whole-house cooling by pulling in air from open windows and exhausting it into  the attic. The whole-house fan is different from an attic fan, which exhausts  hot air from the attic only.
          </p>
          <p><strong>Wood (fuel):<a name="wood" id="wood"></a> </strong>Wood logs, chips, pellets, scraps, or wood products that are burned for  heat. </p>
          <p><strong>Wood or pellet stove<a name="wood1" id="wood1"></a>:</strong> A heating appliance that is freestanding or installed into the  fireplace opening that can burn wood and wood-derived biomass fuel.  Freestanding fireplaces that can be detached from their chimneys are considered  wood or pellet stoves.</p>
   <p><strong>Wood consumption<strong><strong><a name="woodcon"></a></strong></strong>:</strong> The amount of wood burned in a fireplace, stove, or furnace in  the housing unit at any time during the reference year. Respondents report cut  wood or wood logs in cords, which measure approximately 128 cubic feet. Pellets  are reported as the number of 40-pound bags or the number of tons used.</p>
  
          <div class="glossary_title"><a name="x" id="x"></a>XYZ</div><br />
          <p><strong>Year of  construction: </strong>The year the structure was originally completed as reported by the  respondent. </p>
